    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Apply Pythagoras’ theorem, formula transposition, and percentage calculations to verify a cable installation's compliance.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To conclude, we will combine your mathematical skills into a single practical scenario. In electrical work, you often need to determine a physical length before you can calculate electrical properties like resistance.",
      "You will need to use Pythagoras' theorem to find a cable length, transpose a basic formula to find the resistance per meter, and finally use percentage calculations to check if the result meets a specific design limit."
    ],
    "questionText": "A sub-main cable is installed diagonally across a warehouse. The horizontal distance is 24m and the vertical rise is 7m.\n\n1. Calculate the actual length of the cable run using Pythagoras' theorem.\n2. The total measured resistance for this specific run is 0.125 Ω. Using the formula 'Total Resistance = Length × Resistance per meter', transpose this to find the Resistance per meter (Ω/m) for this cable.\n3. If the maximum design limit for this cable type is 0.00625 Ω/m, calculate what percentage of that limit your calculated resistance represents.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Cable Length: 25m (calculated as the square root of 24² + 7²).",
      "Transposed Formula: Resistance per meter = Total Resistance / Length.",
      "Resistance per meter calculation: 0.125 / 25 = 0.005 Ω/m.",
      "Percentage of limit: 80% (calculated as 0.005 / 0.00625 × 100)."
    ],
    "hint": "Start by finding the hypotenuse (the cable length). Then, to transpose the formula, remember: if Length is multiplying on one side, it must divide on the other."
  }
